{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/forget-daily-statistics-of-the-coronavirus-7e9bbb7349bd", "time": 1683006236.041055, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/forget-daily-statistics-of-the-coronavirus-7e9bbb7349bd/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Tired of being told about COVID-19 Direction Changes Every 2nd Day? | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Tired of being told about COVID-19 Direction Changes Every 2nd Day?", "description": "Forget Daily Statistics about the Coronavirus and follow the Right KPI! For most countries, the case statistics follow a weekly pattern, with the bottom during the weekend."}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://github.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19", "anchor_text": "JHU", "paragraph_index": 10}, {"url": "https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/medicine/sph/ide/gida-fellowships/Imperial-College-COVID19-Europe-estimates-and-NPI-impact-30-03-2020.pdf", "anchor_text": "Estimating the number of infections and the impact of non-pharmaceutical interventions on COVID-19 in 11 European countries, 2020-Mar-30, Imperial College", "paragraph_index": 18}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basic_reproduction_number", "anchor_text": "Reproduction Number R0", "paragraph_index": 19}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/create-a-coronavirus-app-using-r-shiny-and-plotly-6a6abf66091d", "anchor_text": "R version", "paragraph_index": 23}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/visualise-covid-19-case-data-using-python-dash-and-plotly-e58feb34f70f", "anchor_text": "Python version", "paragraph_index": 23}], "all_paragraphs": ["We [and the media!] attach too much importance to the Daily Numbers. For most countries, the case statistics follow a weekly pattern, with the bottom during the weekend.", "Replacing the daily figures and its interpretations by a Rolling Average of the Last 7 Days leads to some decisive advantages:", "Let us zoom into the Italian data to better understand this effect:", "In each chart, one of the two metrics is highlighted by a thicker line. Now let us add arrows to indicate the observed directional changes:", "On the left side, we see a red arrow each time we observe a micro-counter-trend, i.e. a directional change in the daily numbers against the main trend. 9 times we got a \u201cwrong signal\u201d (or \u201cmisinterpretation\u201d).", "On the right side, we do not have a single wrong signal! The single directional change corresponds to the correct break of the macro-trend by End of March \u2014 indicated by a green arrow.", "Now we realise easily that Italy has been following a consistent downward trend for 4 weeks.", "What we identified as \u201cwrong signal\u201d is what we stated as \u201cmisinterpretation\u201d or \u201coverhasty conclusion\u201d at the beginning. The exact definition we used in the calculations is:", "A directional change is considered a \u201cmisinterpretation of numbers\u201d if the direction is reverted in less than 5 days.", "Back to the overall data set.", "We used the data from JHU and analyzed the data for 117 countries from the individual outbreaks of the virus (>5 cases per million population) until 2020-Apr-20. The average reduction of misinterpretations in these countries would have been 60%. For many countries the reductions are even higher. Examples of such countries include:", "Let us have a quick look at these countries :", "Obviously, the Rolling 7-Day Average (green line) is again way smoother than the daily figures. But much more important \u2014 the Rolling Average changes its direction much less times!", "The effect shown for Confirmed Cases is also valid for the Deaths. We get the same advantage in applying the Rolling Average on that metric.", "There might be different reasons for the (mostly weekly) patterns:", "Even if the reason for the \u2018seasonality\u2019 is another one, smoothing the data by taking the 7-day averages makes the results much more stable.", "The existence of seasonal patterns in the data should also be incorporated in prediction models. Adjusting for the seasonality effect makes predictions more accurate and its credibility (or confidence) intervals narrower.", "There are already a lot of very good forecasting models out there, e.g.", "Estimating the number of infections and the impact of non-pharmaceutical interventions on COVID-19 in 11 European countries, 2020-Mar-30, Imperial College.", "This study examines the different interventions countries have taken: event banning, school closures, lockdown, etc., and its impact measured in terms of reduction in the Reproduction Number R0 (or Rt). Very interesting read!", "The average person has no advantage in seeing the COVID-19 numbers changing its direction every few days. It rather creates additional unnecessary panic and uncertainty.", "After all, these quick shifts in direction have nothing to do with successfully implemented interventions (like \u201cstay-at-home\u201d) but are often an artifact of weekends. Therefore \u2014 again:", "Some weeks ago I created a tiny web app to visualize Coronavirus case statistics. Now I added the Rolling 7-Day Average, so if you want to check the numbers of your country or US state, follow this link:", "And if you want to create such an app by yourself (with R or Python) check my more technical 101 articles: R version, Python version.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Manager Digital & AI @ GKN Hydrogen. Strong statistics and Machine Learning background. Loves excellent UI & UX. Creative and always open to new ideas."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F7e9bbb7349bd&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fforget-daily-statistics-of-th